// Q7: Why Pyramid Principle Works
::Q7 Why Pyramid Principle Works::Why does the Pyramid Principle recommend leading with conclusions rather than building to them?{
=Because readers trust you've done the analysis and want the answer first#Correct! The lecture explains that readers trust you've done the bottom-up thinking. They want the answer first (top-down presentation) so they can choose how deep to go. This respects their time.
~Because conclusions are always longer than supporting arguments#Incorrect. Length has nothing to do with the Pyramid Principle's logic. Conclusions are often shorter than arguments.
~Because chronological order is confusing to executives#Incorrect. While executives prefer concise communication, the Pyramid Principle isn't specifically about avoiding chronological order — it's about presenting conclusions first.
~Because it makes documents look more professional#Incorrect. The Pyramid Principle is about clarity and reader processing, not visual professionalism. It works because it matches how minds process information.
####Understanding
}

// Q8: MECE Principle Purpose (True/False)
::Q8 MECE Principle Purpose::In the MECE principle, "Mutually Exclusive" means arguments can overlap as long as they collectively cover all relevant points.{FALSE#Correct! "Mutually Exclusive" means arguments must NOT overlap — each must be distinct with no redundancy. The lecture example showed "Increase revenue" and "Expand into new markets" violate MECE because they overlap (expansion is one way to increase revenue). Arguments must be both mutually exclusive (no overlap) AND collectively exhaustive (cover everything).#Incorrect. This contradicts the definition of "Mutually Exclusive." If arguments overlap, they violate MECE's first requirement. The principle requires both separation (mutually exclusive) AND completeness (collectively exhaustive).####Understanding}

// Q9: Active Voice Benefits
::Q9 Active Voice Benefits::Why does the lecture recommend using active voice in business writing?{
=Because active voice clarifies responsibility and sounds more confident#Correct! The lecture explains that active voice clarifies who is responsible ("We recommend" vs. "It is recommended") and sounds more confident. Business writing should be 80%+ active voice.
~Because passive voice is grammatically incorrect#Incorrect. Passive voice is grammatically correct and has limited uses (when the actor is unknown or irrelevant). The issue is clarity, not correctness.
~Because active voice always makes sentences shorter#Incorrect. While active voice often shortens sentences, this isn't always true. The main benefit is clarity of responsibility, not length.
~Because passive voice is only used in academic writing#Incorrect. Passive voice appears in many writing contexts. The lecture notes it can signal evasion in business writing ("Mistakes were made" avoids blame).
####Understanding
}

// Q10: Specificity in Business Writing (True/False)
::Q10 Specificity in Business Writing::According to Strunk & White's Rule 3, using vague qualifiers like "significantly," "many," and "soon" undermines credibility because readers want specific, measurable information.{TRUE#Correct! The lecture teaches "Use definite, specific, concrete language" as Rule 3. Vague language (e.g., "Sales increased significantly") makes readers ask "How much?" Specific language (e.g., "Sales increased 23% quarter-over-quarter") builds credibility by demonstrating expertise and giving readers data for decisions.#Incorrect. Specificity is central to professional business writing. The lecture explicitly contrasts vague ("many customers complained") with specific ("47 customers filed complaints — 15% of total base") to show how specificity builds trust.####Understanding}

